### Controlling Loop Execution

`break` and `continue` give you **control** over loop execution.

---

### Break -- Exit the Loop

`break` **terminates** the loop immediately:

```js
for (let i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
  if (i === 5) {
    break; // Loop stops when i is 5
  }
  console.log(i); // Prints: 1, 2, 3, 4
}
```

### Continue -- Skip an Iteration

`continue` **skips** the rest of the current iteration and moves to the next:

```js
for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
  if (i === 3) {
    continue; // Skip 3
  }
  console.log(i); // Prints: 1, 2, 4, 5
}
```

---

### Practical Examples

**Break -- Search and Stop**
```js
let numbers = [3, 7, 2, 9, 1, 6];
for (let n of numbers) {
  if (n === 9) {
    console.log("Found 9!");
    break; // No need to continue searching
  }
}
```

**Continue -- Skip Unwanted Values**
```js
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
  if (i % 2 === 0) {
    continue; // Skip even numbers
  }
  console.log(i); // Only odd numbers: 1, 3, 5, 7, 9
}
```

---

> **When to use what:** Use `break` to **stop** a loop when found. Use `continue` to **skip** certain values.

codeExample:
for (let i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
  if (i === 4) {
    console.log("Skipping 4");
    continue;
  }
  if (i === 8) {
    console.log("Stopping at 8");
    break;
  }
  console.log(i);
}
